<DOC><DOCNO> AP890424-0202 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 2135EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-24 0398</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0411</SECOND><HEAD>Thunderstorms in the Midwest</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Strong thunderstorms unleashed heavy rain and golf ball-sizedhail Monday in the upper Midwest, and spring snow fell inmountainous sections of the West. Temperatures hit record highs inKansas, Nebraska and Missouri.   Isolated strong thunderstorms struck in northwest Iowa, southcentral Minnesota and northeastern North Dakota.   Large hail fell in or near the Iowa cities of Spencer, Everlyand Royal, and on Cando, N.D. One Iowa storm dumped heavy rain,including 3{ inches of rain near Hartly and 2{ inches in Sutherland.   Scattered showers and thunderstorms also fell in western Texas,and from eastern Kentucky to western North Carolina and northernSouth Carolina.   Rain and some thunderstorms fell in northern and centralCalifornia and western Oregon.   Snow continued to fall at higher altitudes in northernCalifornia, as well as in the mountains of southern Oregon. Snowadvisories remained in effect in Oregon for the southern Cascadesand the Siskiyou Mountains.   Snow also fell in Nevada and New Hampshire. Two inches fell inthe same six-hour period in Winnemucca, Nev., and Mount Washington,N.H.   Temperatures climbed into the 90s in western and central Kansasand southeast Nebraska.   Records for the date were set in Concordia, Kan., where it was89 degrees, 1 degree over the 1954 mark; Kansas City, Mo., (88degrees, 84 degrees in 1986); Lincoln, Neb., (91, 90 in 1960); andin St. Joseph, Mo. (89, 87 in 1986).   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 30degrees in South Lake Tahoe, Calif., to 99 degrees in Hays, Kan.The nation's low Monday morning was 17 degrees in Gunnison, Colo.   Tuesday's forecast called for scattered showers andthunderstorms from the northern Plains and the upper MississippiValley to the central Plains and the Texas Panhandle; rain showersfrom the central and southern Pacific Coast to the northern andcentral Intermountain region to Montana; snow across the northernRockies; and snow showers in northern Maine.   High temperatures were predicted in the 40s in the northernRockies and northern Maine; the 50s and 60s from the Pacific Coastto the intermountain region, much of the northern Plains, northernMinnesota, the Great Lakes and New England; the 90s from westernTexas to much of Kansas and Missouri and to southern Illinois andgenerally in the 70s and 80s in the rest of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>